docs.lead_paragraph: Joseph R. Biden Jr.’s presidential campaign is naming Representative Cedric Richmond to a major leadership role within the organization, a move that could bolster Mr. Biden’s standing with some congressional Democrats and African-American leaders in politically important states, even as the former vice president faces scrutiny over his record on criminal justice issues.

headline.main: Cedric Richmond, Biden’s New Co-Chairman, Sees a Path to the Nomination in the South

docs.abstract: Mr. Biden is the early pacesetter in the South Carolina primary, buoyed by his long ties to elected officials there. But some question whether his support will endure.

docs.lead_paragraph: WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. — In most respects it was a typical first Sunday at Brookland Baptist Church. The minister delivered a raucous sermon, communion was distributed and the choir closed the service with the gospel classic “Order My Steps,” which admonishes Christians that “Satan is busy, God is real.”

headline.main: Joe Biden Has Support From Older Black Voters. Is It Enough?

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For the first time in two decades, Democratic presidential candidates are engaged in a politically fraught debate on gun-control policy as campaigns and advocacy groups assess the nation’s evolving views of an issue long considered a land mine for the left.

headline.main: Gun Issues, Long at the Fringe, Now Loom Large for Democratic Candidates
headline.print_headline: Issue of Gun Control, Long Hedged, Becomes Platform for Democrats

docs.lead_paragraph: OAKLAND, Calif. — Senator Elizabeth Warren bounded onto stage before a crowd of more than 6,000 here — “the biggest one so far,” she announced excitedly — and stayed for nearly two extra hours, past 11 p.m., until everyone who wanted a picture with her had gotten one.
